segments.text: Okay, well, my name is Mary Elaine Miller.
My maiden name is Kraus.
K-R-A-U-S. No, no, E. Oh, okay.
From, where did Kraus come from?
Well, my dad was from Detroit.
Okay.
And his ancestry all...
originated in Detroit or Germany?
I mean, you went back a couple of generations at Detroit, and then prior to that they were in Germany.
I was fishing to see if you were Texas or something.
I'm not a Texas debt lawyer.
No, I'm a Texan by choice.
Actually, I wasn't even by choice.
I was dragged in kicking and screaming, but once I got here, I loved it.
I was in a sense.
My father told the three sons, three kids rather, three sons and daughter, we could go to school anywhere we wanted to as long as it wasn't Louisiana where we live.
That's where I grew up.
Because my mom, her maiden name is Troianni, and she's from New Orleans.
And when I was very young, well, I actually was born in Key West, Florida.
My dad was in the Navy.
My mom and dad met in New Orleans, and they got married, and then she went to Key West with him.
This was all during the war.
And then when I was young, we moved to New Orleans.
And I actually grew up in New Orleans.
Oh, did you?
OK. And lived there until I was 21, at which time I moved.
Oh, yeah.
I tell people that I've lived in several different places, but New Orleans is the most interesting of them.
So I claim that as home.
I was born there, but we grew up in Natchitoches.
Oh, yeah.
You grew up in New Orleans, basically.
Right, and I went to school there also.
I went to Loyola.
Oh, did you?
Okay.
And I got a bachelor's degree in psychology.
I'm trying to think.
A junior history professor probably knows at Loyola.
I used to know.
Father, O'Neal.
Oh, yes, I did know Father O'Neal.
Did you know Father O'Neal?
You bet.
I surely did.
He was a character.
He could tell stories.
He was wonderful.
I'll tell you, the biggest character there, and this guy was really weird, this kind of pilier.
He taught theology.
But I remember O'Neill.
I remember O'Neill sitting and regaling us with New Orleans, I guess it was a dialect.
He couldn't.
imitate the language from each different block.
Oh, really?
Oh, I love that.
The pure Brooklyn.
Yeah, my brother sounds like a Brooklyn cab driver.
Yeah, I had aunts who lived in New Orleans, and they liked me in the Prince Porter area.
And they were so amazing.
Oh, yes.
I thought that was interesting.
So, Loyola, psychology?
Yeah, and then after that, I went up to Princeton.
I actually had a very short-lived marriage that took me to Princeton.
My husband was a graduate student there, and I worked in the psychology department and just took some courses there.
My marriage didn't survive, but I met my present husband at Princeton, and then we ended up at Michigan State.
Okay.
My father went to Michigan State.
We've got all kinds of connections, haven't we?
Isn't it funny how people just travel in the same circle?
Well, then at Michigan State, I did not work at the university.
I worked for the state of Michigan.
And I went into social work.
And I actually took a lot of courses at the university because I had, at that time, attended to try to go to law school.
Well, actually, I was going to go to law school.
And then I was going to go to medical school.
So I took courses for years in all the basics that I needed.
And then I ended up doing neither one.
But I worked in social work and then went into supervision.
And then I was a case worker for the state.
And that was before it was split into income maintenance and child welfare.
It was together at the time.
So you worked with the entire families and did both the income maintenance part and the social work aspect.
And then I became a supervisor.
And then my career just kind of evolved in an entirely different direction away from social work.
I had almost a...

life-changing experience in social work where a young woman that I had worked with and really loved as a matter of fact and we just developed such an affection before I had a baby she went into a mental institution we had to take the baby away place the baby elsewhere and I had to go

testify in court again about her incompetence as a parent and she ended up killing herself and that was and and she was like a younger sister to me i mean that's how much i had become attached to her and i realized at that moment that you don't change people they change themselves and i wasn't i wasn't the person to do it so anyway i went into supervision and then i got into management into training
and then into management development, and had a wonderful director by the name of Jack Dempsey.
He was known all over the state.
He was the governor's right-hand man, and he was known in Washington.
He was highly respected everywhere in political and welfare system.
circles and he died prematurely from lung cancer.

He was a chain smoker but he gave me wonderful opportunities for development and I ended up traveling all over the country really on different projects and was able to get a half million dollar grant to run what we were calling an organizational development project.
and it was a demonstration project for the federal government demonstrating how if you change the, I mean it was really state of the art with regard to management techniques.
If you change the way
you manage the people in an organization, you're going to change the way the organization produces.
And so we did some really in-depth, creative management development with all managers and supervisors in different organizations around the state.
and wrote up a two-year study.
You were mainly in state agencies or federal agencies?
No, we were working in the state of Michigan welfare agencies in a lot of the different counties.
And we had picked like six demonstration sites.
But in doing so, then, we worked with a couple of other states because they were also involved in the project.
At the end of the two years, we wrote up a report that was just dramatic changes, and it was published by Share, I can't remember, it's been so long, it's been 20 or 25 years.
Anyway, and then I had the opportunity to make presentations all over the country with regard to this project.
As a result, I went from the social work part of it into management and management development.
Then I got into strategic planning and became the director of planning for this large state agency that had 14,000 employees all across the state.
Well, after that, then, I started having children, and we moved to Atlanta.
And so I had decided that while the children were young, I had three of them while they were young.
What was your husband doing there?
My husband had a PhD in chemistry, and he was the vice chair of the chemistry department at Michigan State.
Then he was at Ohio State for a very short time and commuted, actually, on weekends because we never made the move.
And then he went into an instrumentation company, a scientific instrumentation company, Nicolet Instrument, in Atlanta, Georgia, and we moved to Atlanta.
And at that time was when I had the very young children.
So what I did instead of getting a full-time job, I went to work for

Actually, I went to work with one other person in a management consulting firm, and we did some management consulting for the welfare agency in Atlanta and for a couple of other organizations, a bank and what was that?
I can't remember.
But that worked pretty good.
That worked out just fine because I was able to work at home a lot and speak with the children and yet stay in touch with them.
How long ago was that when you were doing that roughly?
That ended about 14 years ago.
Because we moved here.
That kind of an activity, and now everybody's becoming management consultants.
Oh, yeah.
Everything I did, I did at the front end of it, and then dropped it and went into something else.
Yeah, that was before management consulting was quite so popular.
Then we moved here, and I did... And your husband came to the...
He came to the College of Science here.
Okay.
And he was actually the Saba in the College of Science, and then he took over as the Director of Electronic Microscopy, and he's now in Research Administration.
And he does just a tiny little bit of teaching and no research anymore.
But we moved here, and then I...
When did you come to college?
We moved here in 1984, and in 86, I came to work for the university.
So I've been here about 11 years.
And what was your first employment?
I was the Director of Operations Analysis, which was the group that did operational reviews on campus.
Under whom?
Under Robert Smith.
Robert hired me and I worked at him until he retired.
And then after a couple of years of that job, I became Assistant Vice President for Finance and Administration.
And I am now Associate Vice President for Administration.
Let me get those titles correct.
Assistant Vice President for Finance and Administration.
And then, and now...
I'm associate vice president for administration because we split finance and administration into two divisions.
When Robert became the vice president, we put the two divisions together.
Who is the vice president for finance?
Bill Crump.
Where's Danny Parker in the home?
Danny Parker is with the provost.
He's the head of the fiscal part of Ron Douglas.
Thank you.
20 years ago.
OK, now, and let's see.
When does the press come into your focus?
OK.
As I said, I was the head of operations analysis.
When I came over to be assistant vice president for finance and administration, I still had responsibility for operations analysis.
I had responsibility for human resources.
I had responsibility for parking and a couple of other departments.
But the key ones were operations analysis, which did exactly what it said.
I mean, they looked at organizations and analyzed where they were going wrong.
and for human resources, which meant that we worked with the people side of it.
And that's really what my talent is and my interest is in organizational analysis and particularly how you make people work effectively together in organizations, team building, things like that.
Well, Rick Stetter reported to Bill Mobley, the president at the time,
And Rick was having some real serious problems with managing his organization.
And so Bill sent him to me, to talk to me, and I spent several hours, several sessions that were like two hours long each, working with Rick on what he could do.
Good.
I was glad to hear that.
That clarifies a lot.
Okay.
Thank you.
Working with Rick on what he could do to get it back at the price.
And he was very open, as you said, about all the things that he did wrong.
Yes, yes.
He would come to me and hang his head and say, this is what I've done.
And I would work with him and say, Rick,
These are the kinds of things that you need to do if you want to be able to work effectively with the people in your organization.
And he would make notes, and I gave him a book to read on the seven habits of highly effective people and things like that.
And we talked about how he could set some goals with his people because their acquisitions were declining, their publications were declining, people were not working together effectively.
And one thing I said to him was, Rick, stop discussing your personal business with your employees.
Just stop.
Yeah, and Noah said he told him that over and over again.
Rick wrote it all down.
He said, yes, yes, I know exactly what to do.
He would walk out of my office pumped up, enthusiastic, and never did a thing.
Would come back a month later.
And I finally said, Rick, you're not doing anything that you know you have to do.
You're not going to succeed.
So he finally left.
And this was at, I remember, this was at a Mother's Club coffee on a Saturday morning in the fall, just as Rick, Rick was on extended sick leave at the time.
Actually, he was just, they were, they just tried to get him to go home.
And Bill Mobley and Robert Smith and I and Dean Gage, who was the provost, were standing around talking about the press and what we were going to do with the press.
And Rick apparently had talked to Bill Mobley and suggested that I be involved in any decision about the future of the press, because Rick, I think, really respected my opinion.
He just couldn't do anything with the information.
And so Bill Mobley said to me, well, what do you know about
And I said, well, I read books.
And that's a common denominator, incidentally.
Oh, is that right?
Yes, it is.
Everybody who's in there, you know, it's an accidental profession, they call it.
No one plans to go into publishing.
And what is the ties between them?
They all like books.
They really do, no matter who, from clerks on up or down.
Oh, well, that's interesting.
I said, well, I read books.
And he said, well, that's good enough.
That's right, yeah.
He said, I'd like you to go in.
And just see what you can do to pull that group back into a team until we can find the right director.
And so that's how I ended up there.
Not because I had any strength in publishing at all, but because I had strength in helping people.
So that's how I got there.
Excellent.
Thank you.
That helped so much.
That's a good story.
And I used most of all of that.
You can read and edit it as you like.
I think I handled these things better.
So you go to the press.
What month was that?
Do you remember?
I believe that was in October.
Oh no, that was before 95.
That was October of 94, I guess.
End of September, beginning of October, something like that.
And I remember at the time that that's when I was also chairing the Shots Across Brazos Valley.
I don't know if you remember that, where we did the flu shots and the immunizations.
Well, that was eating my lunch for the first two or three months that I was there.
And so I was very stressed out.
And everyone there had, I mean, I think they were wondering, what is this animal that came here, you know, that's still doing assistant vice president work,

is consumed with this community project that you know i was doing before the university and is here trying to help us but we we worked through it and they were wonderful people and very accepting yeah they are
Now, what I had known, you asked me what were my impressions before and after I got there.
What I had known about before I got in was only through Rick.
I'd never met anybody there before I walked in the door the first, well actually Dean took me over a week before and introduced me.
But prior to that I'd never known any of them.
And so Rick had told me about different
people that gave me an insight into their strengths and some of their strengths and weaknesses.
So I had formed some opinions before I ever got there, some of which were right and some of which were not right.
But I had a pretty good sense of the kind of disharmony that existed in the organization and the backbiting.
And that was just reinforced when I got there.
I mean, I think my impressions were
fairly accurate but I didn't have any idea of the depth of the pain that existed in that organization.
They had allowed themselves to
to be practically destroyed.
Yeah.

And the one question that I kept asking them after I really saw how painful it was for them, the one question that I asked so many of them was, how could you have ever given one person that kind of power over your life that you would allow him to have that negative impact on you?
Yeah.
And what answer did you get?
It was almost like
They had not thought of it that way, but they had released that power themselves.
I said, you didn't have to let Rick come in and destroy your relationships.
You let that happen.
And I was going to say, one of the answers might indeed be that this is the way they were brought up, which was the Wardlaw syndrome.
Well, it could be.
They were under the control.
Because they talked about it.
They didn't think for themselves.
They talked to Wardlaw as the father figure.
And there's not, you know, Lloyd didn't have quite that connotation, but he still continuously
That's right.
The Wardlaw era.
And I think he did it consciously, deliberately.
Well, probably.
I'm sure he was trying.
Possibly.
He was probably trying to be another Frank Wardlaw, because...
I don't think so.
I think he was using the Franks.
Oh, really?
I really do.

friendship with lloyd but the more i looked at this you know he gave so many benefits continued to toot frank wardlaw and this is not necessarily natural you know well let's face it i mean unless you have an enormous ego it would be really hard to follow in those footsteps exactly yeah
So I think he used the Barlow image deliberately to continue to cultivate this aura, and it worked.
I mean, you know, you keep Joe Moore, and you kept John Lindsay, and you kept all the rest of the boys in the corral, literally.
And it was amazing.
And I think, I may be totally wrong, but this is kind of the way I see it.
I think the culture and the whole place is a family culture, and they have a father image of their directors,
And they preferred to do that.
And Rick certainly could not provide that, nor did he need to.
I mean, what he needed to do was what I ended up having to do by necessity, because I knew nothing about the business.
And that was let them do their jobs.
And that was my focus.
And Rotell and I kind of touched on this a little bit.
And I talked to him about it.
And we talked about the family culture.
And he said, yeah, and I'm uncomfortable with that.
Yeah, they acknowledge now to me that he is not, that he is uncomfortable with that.
And maybe they just need to recognize that those days are over.
That's it.
That's it.
And in fact, the way I think of it is they have to grow up and stand on their own two feet.
It was such a close-knit society in a peculiar way.
They're open, you know, there are a lot of people eating out, but by the same token, they're very tight-knit.
Well, I'm hoping that if I brought anything to that organization, it was two things.

One is that I restored or maybe built a team, because I'm not sure how much the team actually existed or whether the decisions were just doled out by the head, but that I helped to build them into a team.
And the other is that I helped them to stand on their own two feet, because as I said, I couldn't make the decisions for them.
All I could do was to push them to make their own decisions.
So kind of to help them to grow up and to become a mature press rather than the fledgling press that I saw when I first got there.
That they were still, you know, kind of a baby press.
That helps.
That fits pretty well where I'm moving, I think, between the two of you.
Well, this is what I found when I first got there.
I wrote down some negative things that I found and some positive things.
I found that they were basically immobilized.
And they had been that way, I think, for a couple of years.
They had declining acquisitions, declining production, because they couldn't work.
They were so consumed with talking about their problems and focusing on their problems and thinking about their problems that they weren't working on their business.
They wasted a tremendous amount of time.
There was a lot of paranoia in the organization, a lot of back-fighting.
There were closed doors with two people sitting in there talking about something else that was going on in the organization.
A lot of frustration, and I mean professional frustration because they didn't feel like they were doing anything with their careers.
There was some sorrow because many of them who had been there a while knew the glory of the press, and it wasn't there at all anymore.
They felt that sense of loss.
In fact, when I walked in there, oh, I heard about for ages was Frank Ward Law and what it used to be like.
And if I didn't have such a strong ego of mine, I mean, if I didn't have so much...
of my own personal sense of satisfaction, I think I'd have been crushed.
Crushed by the ward law, yeah.
But I didn't feel sensitive about it at all.
They were working against one another, and there was completely inadequate communication.
I mean, they didn't talk enough about anything with regard to the business.
On the positive side...
What I found were people who were tremendously talented and tremendously dedicated to that organization.
They loved the business that they're in.
They absolutely loved it.
But even more than that, they loved the press.
The Texas A&M University Press.
They loved that organization.
And they hated what was happening to it.
They had wonderful relationships with their operatives.
And they had a real eagerness to get back on track.
They just didn't have a clue how to do it.
So with that, we set about... How did you find all this out?
Just talking to them and watching them.
Because that's one thing I did pick up.
You were always there.
You were always to be seen.
And that really helped, they said.
Because it kind of gave, it was an open door in itself.
And I think that's one of the expressions somebody used.
When you came in, the door was open.
All the doors opened.
In fact, I told them not to close the doors.
Good!
I said, I didn't want, you know, Diana Hine used to, her door was always closed and locked when she was not there.
And I said, no more.
The door stays open.

I said, if you've got something that other people can't see, first I would be puzzled as to what that was, but if it's something confidential, you put it in a file cabinet, you lock it, and you give someone else the key so that if we need to get out, we can't.
Your computer doesn't get locked up so that nobody can, you know, retrieve your information.
Bonnie and Jim really did pretty well.
I mean, he laughed, I think, because of the stresses and the strange things he did.
I think he was a smoker and they didn't like smoking.
Oh, yeah.
They resented him, too.
They resented the arrangement that Rick made with him.
Yeah, did they?
They really resented him.
In fact, they resented a lot of one another.
Wonderful people.
And they have been such a tight, productive group.
And one of the things you said that I think it was a useful sense of work ethic, and that is that everything we do, everyone has touched.
Each book has been touched by everybody in the state.
That was a nice expression.
We all do this together.
And I think, and they may have lost that, but I think it's
It's coming back, but it's still there.
But I thought that expressed, indeed, the sense of cohesion and basic work ethic in the group.
Well, I think that's what I tried to do when I got there.
See, the way that I believe in communication, I believe that that's the answer to most of the problems.
Just talk about them.
And so that's what I tried to do.
And if ever I heard a rumbling, I would try to bring in the two people who were having the problem and get them to talk it out.
And sometimes it didn't work, but most of the time it did.
I tried to open up the business to everybody.
We would have, and in fact, I think it drove them crazy.
And when Tom came in, he immediately stopped what I had started.
But I think what I did was real important at the time.
We would have weekly or biweekly, I mean semiweekly.
Sometimes I think it was twice a week.
I can't remember.
But very frequent staff meetings with large groups of people.
And we would talk about everything.
And some of them were very resentful at the beginning.
They'd say, why are you having these people talk about my business?
I do the acquisitions.
I do the editing.
I do the working with the printers and all that.
Why is everybody getting involved in my business?
And they were getting very defensive.
And we worked on that and worked on it and worked on it.
And I said, as long as I'm here, your business is their business.
Everybody's business is together.
And I tried real hard to emphasize this notion of internal customers.
that their primary customers were one another.
I took the entire staff on a retreat.
I think it was a two-day retreat.
We didn't stay over.
We drove back and forth.
We went down to Camp Allen.
And the entire staff, including Mike in the warehouse, the only people who stayed behind were student workers.
And we talked about the purpose of the press, the goals that we had for the press,
communication styles.
We played games.
We did team building kinds of things.
And this was my emphasis the entire 18 months that I was there, was to try to get them working together as a team.
And they're doing the publishing job.
Your job is to get them to do the publishing job.
That's right.
And they would come to me with questions about publishing.
And I would say, that's your expertise.
Although I learned an awful lot, and I did end up making a lot of decisions.
And I'll tell you, the reason that I made a lot of decisions is because they were very conservative about what they were willing...
They confessed that conservative... And I used to push them to stretch their limits, you know.
Oh, you're ordering 20,000 copies?
I think you can sell 25.
Order 25.
I made some mistakes, but that's OK.
They just stretched and stretched.
They probably got that extra 5,000 sitting in the warehouse now.
They didn't want to do certain types of books.
I said, why not?
That's ridiculous.
And Noel would say things like, we don't do poetry.
And I said, I can't believe that if you ended up with a Robert Frost manuscript that you wouldn't publish it.
Well.
Incidentally, I'm still kind of thinking this one over.
Frank Wardlaw turned down a DeBakey manuscript in 1977.
Well, they... Because we don't do medicine.
Right.
That's right.
Well, I said, you know, we'll do whatever is, you know, whatever we can do a good job of doing.
We won't take on things that
that obviously we're going to fail with, but on the other hand, we're going to really stretch.
Did you begin to sense at some point a turnaround?
Yeah, I did.
First of all, we're in the Borderlands.
We're doing the Borderlands series.
And that was one of the things that I had really pushed.
Because I thought, it's an excellent opportunity.
We've got people on our, whatever the board is called, the fundraising board, who are from Laredo.
They're interested in us as a press.
They're interested in helping us.
